SIMPLE: scalene
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scalene
<hw>Sca*lene"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>scalenus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>scal⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Having the sides and
angles unequal; -- said of a triangle.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having
the axis inclined to the base, as a cone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Designating several
triangular muscles called <xex>scalene muscles</xex>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Of or pertaining to the scalene muscles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scalene muscles</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a group
of muscles, usually three on each side in man, extending from the
cervical vertebrae to the first and second ribs.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scalene</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scalene
<hw>Sca*lene"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A triangle
having its sides and angles unequal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scalenohedral</ent>⟦br⟧
